    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
            <ab>
                <lb n="1"/><persName type="divine"><name type="divine" key="Marcurius Mercurius">Marcurio</name></persName> 
                <lb n="2"/><persName><name type="gentilicium" key="Fonteius"><expan><abbr><unclear>F</unclear>ont</abbr><ex>eius</ex></expan></name></persName> dono <expan><abbr>ded</abbr><ex>it</ex></expan>.</ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>Font(eius?) gave this as a gift to Mercury.</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>This is a votive offering made possibly by a man named Fonteius (or possibly
                    Fontaeus, Fontenius or Fontinius) to the god Mercury. Fonteius may have been of high social status, the votive offering is
                    made of bronze and is well-made. It has been suggested that the finger is an
                    anatomical votive offering in thanks or expectation of healing, although such an
                    offering for Mercury is unusual as he is not a god of healing. It would be an
                    unusual anatomical votive offering for several other reasons: first, prolonged
                    pain or sickness that would lead to prayer for healing would usually afflict the
                    whole hand, not a single finger, and there are indeed examples of hand-shaped
                    anatomical offerings from the Republic. Second, anatomical votive offerings from
                    the Republican period are usually made of terracotta and produced with moulds.
                    Earlier votive offerings from the Veneto were made of metal, but are flat
                    miniatures, not full-scale realistic representation of the afflicted organ as
                    the finger is. Third, very few of the terracotta anatomical votives were
                    inscribed. While it is possible that the finger is a highly unusual votive
                    offering, the combination of anomalies make it very unlikely. There are,
                    however, many dedications to Mercury from Republican Italy. Therefore it is more
                    likely that this is simply a votive offering, possibly a part of a larger statue,
                    as the tang at the end of the finger may suggest.</p></div>
            

